# Day 15: Introduction to Cloud Databases

Cloud databases eliminate the operational overhead of installing, patching, and backing up data storage instances. They generally fall into two categories: Relational (SQL) options like AWS RDS or Azure SQL, which maintain strict schemas and transactional consistency, and Non-Relational (NoSQL) options like DynamoDB or MongoDB Atlas, engineered for flexible data schemas, horizontal scalability, and high throughput workloads.

## Detailed Breakdown
Cloud computing represents a paradigm shift in how computing resources are consumed.[cite: 1] In the past, companies had to forecast demand and purchase hardware months in advance.[cite: 1] This often led to either under-provisioning (losing customers) or over-provisioning (wasting money).[cite: 1]

With the cloud, we treat 'Infrastructure as Code'.[cite: 1] This means we can script the creation of servers, databases, and networks just like we write software.[cite: 1] This programmability allows for 'Auto-scaling', where the system grows during peak traffic hours and shrinks when users are offline, ensuring maximum cost efficiency.[cite: 1]

Furthermore, cloud providers offer 'High Availability' by spreading data centers across different geographical regions.[cite: 1] If one data center fails due to a power outage or natural disaster, your application can automatically failover to another location without the end-user even noticing.[cite: 1]

### Key Takeaway for Today:
The cloud provides democratization of technology.[cite: 1] A startup with two employees now has access to the same world-class infrastructure as a Fortune 500 company, paying only for the minutes they use.[cite: 1]
